'''''Laowai''''' is the [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin]] pronunciation/transliteration of {{lang|zh|{{linktext|老外}}}} ([[pinyin]]: ''lǎowài'', <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"constantly foreign or old foreign"), an informal term or slang for "foreigner" and/or non-Chinese national, usually neutral but possibly impolite or loose in some circumstances.<ref>The "talk page" might be able to provide more information on the controversy of the term.</ref> Formal and polite Chinese terms for foreigner include ''wàiguórén'' ({{zh|t={{linktext|外國人}}|s={{linktext|外国人}}|l=foreigner}}), ''wàibīn'' ({{zh|s={{linktext|外宾}}|t={{linktext|外賓}}|l=foreigner guest|labels=no}}), ''guójì yǒurén'' {{zh|s={{linktext|国际|友人}}|t={{linktext|國際|友人}}|l=international friend|labels=no}}) and ''wàiguó pengyou'' ({{zh|s={{linktext|外國|朋友}}|t={{linktext|外国|朋友}}|l=foreigner friend|labels=no}}).<ref>"[http://www.waze.net/china/laowai.php Culture: Seven Ways to Say 'Foreigner']". 17 Mar 2004. Accessed 15 Jun 2014.</ref> The term is typically used to refer to Europeans ('whites', 'Caucasians') especially, and to a lesser extent, Africans ('black'), Native Americans, Latin Americans and Middle Easterners.<ref>Mair, Victor. "[http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=11626 Laowai: the old furriner]" at ''Language Log''. 9 Apr 2014. Accessed 15 Jun 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jiangxi.jxnews.com.cn/system/2013/02/08/012285502.shtml|title=老外喜过中国年-中国年-江西新闻网|work=jxnews.com.cn}}</ref> "Laowai" usually does not refer to ethnic Han of non-Chinese nationality or other East Asian ethnicities.
==Etymology== The use of the word {{zh|c={{linktext|老外}}|labels=no}} began in the 1980s, as an abbreviation of the term {{linktext|外國人}} (foreigner) into {{lang|zh|{{linktext|外}}}} (foreign or outside) plus the character {{lang|zh|{{linktext|老}}}} (old). It can have positive associations, indicating age or experience&mdash;such as ''lǎopéngyou'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|老|朋友}}|l=old friend|labels=no}})&mdash;or respect, as in the familiar use of ''lǎo'' to denote the senior and respected members of families or to address teachers ({{zh|s={{linktext|老師}}|t={{linktext|老师}}|labels=no}}, ''lǎoshī''). It may also be used in combination with part of a person's name (usually the family name) to refer to that person in a familiar and respectful way (for example a person with the surname [[Zhou (surname)|周]], or Zhōu, could be referred to as 老周, literally "Old Zhōu"). This usage is reserved exclusively for adults, but implies familiarity rather than seniority, and is often attached to specific individuals as a nickname rather than being freely used.
However, in certain contexts, it can also carry negative connotations of being old or aged looking ({{zh|s={{linktext|老頭子}}|t={{linktext|老头子}}|labels=no}}), boring old {{linktext|sticks-in-the-mud}}&mdash;as in ''lǎo gǔdǒng'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|老古董}}}})&mdash;or of years of experience and contempt&mdash;as in ''lǎo dōngxi'' ({{zh|s={{linktext|老東西}}|t={{linktext|老东西}}|labels=no|l=old bastard}}, <small>lit.</small> "old thing"). It may be used in the [[Chinese theater|arts]] or in jokes with the sense of "always" or "very": a famous comedy role was named the ''Lǎoniān'' ([[:zh:相亲 (小品)|老蔫]], "Constantly Listless"). And [[Tom Hardy]] was affectionately known in mainland China as ''Lǎoshī'' ({{nowrap|{{zh|s={{linktext|老|濕}}}},}} <small>[[simplified characters|s]]</small>&nbsp;{{lang|zh|{{linktext|老|湿}}|Constantly Wet|labels=no}}) because of his perpetually shiny hair,<ref>"汤老湿(昵称)" "[https://movie.douban.com/celebrity/1049489/ 汤姆·哈迪 (豆瓣)]"</ref> also because of his role "Eames" in ''[[Inception]]'' (2010) sounds like {{lang|zh|{{linktext|一|摸|湿}}}}.<ref>Eames，被翻译成“一摸湿” - "[http://view.inews.qq.com/a/20150626A00SSR00 已经好久没有一个演员像汤老湿一样，让我们觉得危险了]"</ref> It can also be used as an empty prefix, particularly with animals such as [[tiger]]s ({{zh|c={{linktext|老虎}}|p=lǎohǔ|labels=no}}), [[mouse|mice]] ({{zh|c={{linktext|老鼠}}|p=lǎoshǔ|labels=no}}), and [[eagle]]s ({{zh|s={{linktext|老鹰}}|t={{linktext|老鷹}}|p=lǎoyīng|labels=no}}).
The term has come to be used for specific countries as well, with ''lǎo-'' functioning as a colloquial equivalent for ''-guórén'': ''lǎoměi'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|老|美}}|l=[[US|American]]|labels=no}}), ''lǎomo'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|老|墨}}|l=[[Mexicans|Mexican]]|labels=no}}); even ''lǎozhōng'' ({{lang|zh|{{linktext|老|中}}}}) to refer to Chinese ({{zh|s={{linktext|中國人}}|t={{linktext|中国人}}|p=Zhōngguórén|labels=no}}) themselves.
==Usage== As with [[Spanish language|Spanish]] "[[gringo]]", laowai is not considered a necessarily offensive term by those who choose to use it, but may become so from context (tone, manner, situation, etc.). Among the Chinese, the term is informal and may be used in a neutral, genial, or even good-humored way;<ref name=pd/>. Varyingly, it is ironically embraced, begrudgingly accepted, openly resented, or not minded at all among the Western expatriate community.<ref>''Beyond Beyond Well Being''. "[http://beyondwellbeing.com/al/1998/01/the_laowai_racism_and_personal.html The "Laowai", Racism and Personal Space in China]". 16 Jan 1998. Accessed 15 Jun 2014.</ref><ref>''Shanghai Star''. "[http://www.china.org.cn/english/12952.htm Laowai Is What You Make It]". 18 May 2001, Hosted by China.org, 2001. Accessed 15 Jun 2014.</ref>
The official Chinese press has expressed concern about inappropriate use of laowai and avoids it in all formal reporting.{{refn|Although note its use in such informal human-interest stories as [http://ah.anhuinews.com/system/2012/03/27/004864645.shtml this photo caption] from the Chinese edition of ''[[Anhui News]]''.}} Mark Roswell, known under the stage name [[Dashan]], as one of the most famous Western nationals in China's media industry, has admitted a place for the term but recognizes it as a [[pejorative]], stating that "it is the foreigners [in China] who can't speak any Chinese who are truly 'laowai'" ({{zh|s={{linktext|不|會|說|漢語|的|外國人|那|纔|叫|老外|呢}}|t={{linktext|不|会|说|汉语|的|外国人|那|才|叫|老外|呢}}|labels=no}}).<ref>New Year's Gala (at 186:17). CCTV, 2011.</ref> This in itself, implies that the term laowai is something many, including Dashan himself, would prefer to avoid. Editorials, written by Chinese and non-Chinese, have appeared in English and Chinese language newspapers about the subject, particularly around the time of the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]],<ref name=pd>''People's Daily Online''. "[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90780/91345/6325229.html Is 'Laowai' a negative term?]". 21 Dec 2007. Accessed 15 Jun 2014.</ref> when Chinese governments launched campaigns aimed at curbing use of the term in possibly offensive situations.{{Citation needed|date=May 2014}}
